Function select: (-> Atom %Undefined%) HE-extended committed choice over a nondeterministic stream. The primary form (select stream) returns the first non-empty result. The extended forms (select k stream), (select (search-policy lane) stream), and (select k (search-policy lane) stream) expose bounded selection and explicit search-lane choice.
Parameters:
  Atom Stream expression to evaluate
Return: (type %Undefined%) Selected result, or a bounded packet in the two-argument extended form
Function collect: (-> Atom Expression) HE-extended stream collector paired with select. Evaluates a nondeterministic stream and packages all non-empty results into one expression. The policy form (collect (search-policy lane) stream) makes the search lane explicit.
Parameters:
  Atom Stream expression to evaluate
Return: (type Expression) Collected expression of surviving results
Function once: (-> Atom %Undefined%) Compatibility alias for select. Prefer select in new code. The policy form (once (search-policy lane) stream) is supported for legacy call sites that still want explicit search-lane choice.
Parameters:
  Atom Stream expression to evaluate
Return: (type %Undefined%) First non-empty result from the stream
Function search-policy: (-> Atom Atom) Search-policy literal constructor for explicit controlled-search calls. The current native CeTTa lane is recursive-dependent-proof, and it supports result-order control through (search-policy recursive-dependent-proof), (search-policy recursive-dependent-proof (order reverse)), (search-policy recursive-dependent-proof (order lex)), and (search-policy recursive-dependent-proof (order shortlex)). The lex mode orders results by canonical rendered-atom bytes. The shortlex mode orders results by canonical rendered-atom length first, then bytewise lexical order. ATP and solver lanes are named here for future explicit oracle work, but are not executed by the native evaluator yet.
Parameters:
  Atom Search lane name such as recursive-dependent-proof
Return: (type Atom) Opaque policy atom consumed by select, collect, or once
[(@doc-formal (@item select) (@kind function) (@type (-> Atom %Undefined%)) (@desc "HE-extended committed choice over a nondeterministic stream. The primary form (select stream) returns the first non-empty result. The extended forms (select k stream), (select (search-policy lane) stream), and (select k (search-policy lane) stream) expose bounded selection and explicit search-lane choice.") (@params ((@param (@type Atom) (@desc "Stream expression to evaluate")))) (@return (@type %Undefined%) (@desc "Selected result, or a bounded packet in the two-argument extended form")))]
[(@doc-formal (@item collect) (@kind function) (@type (-> Atom Expression)) (@desc "HE-extended stream collector paired with select. Evaluates a nondeterministic stream and packages all non-empty results into one expression. The policy form (collect (search-policy lane) stream) makes the search lane explicit.") (@params ((@param (@type Atom) (@desc "Stream expression to evaluate")))) (@return (@type Expression) (@desc "Collected expression of surviving results")))]
[(@doc-formal (@item once) (@kind function) (@type (-> Atom %Undefined%)) (@desc "Compatibility alias for select. Prefer select in new code. The policy form (once (search-policy lane) stream) is supported for legacy call sites that still want explicit search-lane choice.") (@params ((@param (@type Atom) (@desc "Stream expression to evaluate")))) (@return (@type %Undefined%) (@desc "First non-empty result from the stream")))]
[(@doc-formal (@item search-policy) (@kind function) (@type (-> Atom Atom)) (@desc "Search-policy literal constructor for explicit controlled-search calls. The current native CeTTa lane is recursive-dependent-proof, and it supports result-order control through (search-policy recursive-dependent-proof), (search-policy recursive-dependent-proof (order reverse)), (search-policy recursive-dependent-proof (order lex)), and (search-policy recursive-dependent-proof (order shortlex)). The lex mode orders results by canonical rendered-atom bytes. The shortlex mode orders results by canonical rendered-atom length first, then bytewise lexical order. ATP and solver lanes are named here for future explicit oracle work, but are not executed by the native evaluator yet.") (@params ((@param (@type Atom) (@desc "Search lane name such as recursive-dependent-proof")))) (@return (@type Atom) (@desc "Opaque policy atom consumed by select, collect, or once")))]
